In Eq. (48), ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document} is the risk-aversion weight for under-fulfillment of the biofuel supply chain’s final products. ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document} seeks to find a trade-off between the solution robustness (which is close to an optimal solution) and the model robustness (which is close to a feasible solution). It is clear that a decision-maker who prefers higher values for ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document} is risk-averse and wishes to avoid a shortage of final biofuel products. However, a risk-taking decision-maker chooses smaller values for ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document}. Therefore, we can find a trade-off between cost and demand fulfillment by changing the value of the risk-aversion weight. The results of our analysis show that with increase in the value of the risk-aversion weight (ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document}), the cost of the biofuel supply chain (which indicates solution robustness) increases, while under-fulfillment of the biofuel supply chain’s final products (which indicates model robustness) decreases. This behavior conveys that at larger risk-aversion weight values, there is a tendency toward an almost feasible solution in all 100 scenarios, at the expense of an increase in total cost. Note that the impacts of the risk-aversion weight on solution robustness and model robustness are consistent with the results provided by Mulvey and Ruszczyński [30].

This analysis helps us to determine a proper value for ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document}. Final-product demand under-fulfillment is entirely avoided by choosing a large value for ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document}. For instance, under any scenario, at ω=20\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega = 20$$\end{document}, the biofuel supply chain ensures zero final-product demand under-fulfillment at an expense of 255 million dollars. On the other hand, a smaller value for ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document} results in a total cost reduction while guaranteeing zero final-product demand under-fulfillment for most of the scenarios. For instance, at ω=15\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega = 15$$\end{document}, the total cost equal 243 million dollars, while the supply chain is robust in 96 out of 100 scenarios. For the rest of the analysis in this paper, we assume that ω=15\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega = 15$$\end{document}. However, depending on decision-makers’ purposes and other possible conditions, ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document} can have other values.

Considering 100 scenarios, Fig. 3 shows that by increasing the risk-aversion weight parameter (ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document}), in both the deterministic and robust cases, the total costs increase. More importantly, Fig. 3 demonstrates that the robust optimization approach is considerably better than the expected value approach. To shed light on this, almost in all problems, the robust optimization approach dominates the deterministic model with respect to the mean of the cost in the economic objective function. The intriguing aspect is that the supremacy of the robust model is improved as the risk-aversion weight (ω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\omega $$\end{document}) increases. This means that in the presence of a high level of uncertainty (e.g., due to lack of historical data) or when managers are risk-averse, the robust model matches better with the biofuel supply chain. The reason the robust model performs better is that the deterministic model assigns the same probability to all 100 scenarios, while the robust model devotes a lower probability to outlier scenarios.
